# .cursorrules — MCP Server Development Rules
# ================================================================
# This file defines the rules for AI assistants (Cursor, Claude, etc.)
# working in this MCP server project.
# ================================================================


# ================================================================
# § 0  LANGUAGE POLICY  ★ HIGHEST PRIORITY — NEVER OVERRIDE ★
# ================================================================
#
# [EN] ALL artifacts produced in this repository MUST be written in English.
#      This includes, without exception:
#        • Source code (all files)
#        • Identifiers: variable names, function names, class names, constants
#        • Inline comments and block comments
#        • JSDoc / docstring content
#        • Log messages and error strings
#        • MCP tool names, descriptions, and JSON Schema fields
#        • Configuration files (keys and string values)
#        • Documentation: README, CHANGELOG, ADRs, wiki pages
#        • Git commit messages, branch names, PR/issue titles and bodies
#        • Test descriptions (describe / it / test labels)
#
# [EN] The ONLY exceptions are:
#        1. This .cursorrules file itself — bilingual to help the developer.
#        2. Test fixtures that intentionally contain non-English source code
#           as sample input data (stored under tests/fixtures/).
#        3. Runtime user input passed through by end-users at call time.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------
# [JA — 開発者向け補足]
# このリポジトリで生成・編集するすべての成果物は英語で書くこと。
# 対象: ソースコード・識別子・コメント・JSDoc・ログ文字列・
#        MCP ツール定義・設定ファイル・ドキュメント・
#        コミットメッセージ・ブランチ名・PR/Issue。
# 例外は上記 1〜3 のみ。
# 日本語で書きたいメモは、このファイル末尾の § 9 に書くこと。
# ----------------------------------------------------------------


# ================================================================
# § 1  PROJECT OVERVIEW
# ================================================================
#
# This repository implements an MCP (Model Context Protocol) server.
# MCP servers expose tools, resources, and prompts that AI assistants
# can call at runtime.
#
# Key principles:
#   • Tools must be globally understandable — English-only interfaces.
#   • Security-first: never expose credentials or PII through tool output.
#   • Deterministic outputs: same input → same structured output.
#   • Confirmation gates for any irreversible or destructive operation.


# ================================================================
# § 2  RECOMMENDED REPOSITORY STRUCTURE
# ================================================================
#
# <project-name>/
# ├── src/
# │   ├── server.ts            # MCP server entry point
# │   ├── tools/               # One file per tool (or tool group)
# │   ├── resources/           # MCP resource handlers (if any)
# │   ├── prompts/             # Prompt templates (English Markdown)
# │   └── utils/               # Shared helpers (validation, redaction …)
# ├── tests/
# │   ├── unit/
# │   ├── integration/
# │   └── fixtures/            # Sample data (non-English content allowed)
# ├── docs/
# │   ├── README.md
# │   ├── ARCHITECTURE.md
# │   └── adr/                 # Architecture Decision Records
# ├── .cursorrules             # This file
# ├── package.json
# └── tsconfig.json


# ================================================================
# § 3  CODING CONVENTIONS
# ================================================================

## 3.1  Language & runtime
# - TypeScript with strict mode (strict: true in tsconfig.json).
# - Target: Node.js LTS. Avoid browser-specific APIs.
# - ESM modules (import/export); no CommonJS require().

## 3.2  Type safety
# - Explicit return types on ALL exported functions and methods.
# - No `any`. Use `unknown` and narrow with type guards.
# - Prefer `interface` for object shapes; `type` for unions/aliases.
# - Use `readonly` wherever mutation is not required.
# - Validate all external input with a schema library (e.g., Zod).

## 3.3  Naming conventions
# +-----------------+--------------------------+--------------------------+
# | Target          | Convention               | Example                  |
# +-----------------+--------------------------+--------------------------+
# | Files           | kebab-case               | schema-parser.ts         |
# | Classes         | PascalCase               | SchemaParser             |
# | Functions       | camelCase                | extractTableList()       |
# | Constants       | SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE     | MAX_RETRY_COUNT          |
# | MCP tool names  | snake_case               | my_tool_name             |
# | JSON properties | camelCase                | { "inputSchema": ... }   |
# +-----------------+--------------------------+--------------------------+

## 3.4  Comments & documentation
# - All comments in English — no exceptions.
# - JSDoc on every exported symbol: @param, @returns, @throws.
# - Inline comments explain WHY, not WHAT.
# - TODO / FIXME / HACK must include a GitHub issue number:
#     // TODO(#42): replace with proper parser

## 3.5  Error handling
# - Never silently swallow errors.
# - Wrap every tool handler in try/catch.
# - Return structured MCP errors on failure:
#     { isError: true, content: [{ type: "text", text: "<actionable message>" }] }
# - Error messages must be actionable:
#     OK  : "File not found at path '/foo/bar'. Check that the path exists."
#     BAD : "File error."
# - Log at `error` level with enough context (tool name, input summary).

## 3.6  Formatting
# - Prettier with default settings (printWidth: 100, singleQuote: true).
# - ESLint with recommended + @typescript-eslint/recommended rules.
# - No trailing whitespace. Newline at end of file.
# - Run `lint` and `type-check` before every commit (enforced by CI).


# ================================================================
# § 4  MCP TOOL DESIGN RULES
# ================================================================

## 4.1  Required fields for every tool
# +---------------+------------------------------------------------------+
# | Field         | Requirement                                          |
# +---------------+------------------------------------------------------+
# | name          | snake_case, globally unique within the server        |
# | description   | 2-4 sentences in plain English; explain purpose,     |
# |               | required inputs, and what is returned                |
# | inputSchema   | JSON Schema draft-07; mark required vs optional      |
# | handler       | TypeScript function; typed input & output            |
# +---------------+------------------------------------------------------+

## 4.2  Confirmation gates
# Any tool that is irreversible or potentially destructive MUST:
#   1. Return a summary and ask "Confirm? (yes/no)" on first call.
#   2. Accept { confirmed: true } in a subsequent call to proceed.
#   3. Validate the flag server-side before executing.

## 4.3  Output format
# - Return structured Markdown in English.
# - Use [UNKNOWN] for values that cannot be determined — never guess.
# - Annotate redacted content with [REDACTED].
# - Flag issues inline:
#     🔴 Security concern  |  🟡 Needs review  |  🟢 Low priority

## 4.4  Idempotency
# - Read-only tools must be fully idempotent.
# - Write tools must document whether they are idempotent.


# ================================================================
# § 5  SECURITY — CRITICAL
# ================================================================
#
# These rules are non-negotiable and must be applied at every layer.

## 5.1  Credential & secret protection
# - NEVER log, store, echo, or return credential values
#   (passwords, API keys, tokens, private keys, connection strings).
# - Redact secrets in file content before passing to LLM or tool output:
#     Pattern: /(?<=[=:]\s*['"])[^'"]{4,}/g  =>  "***REDACTED***"
# - Run hardcoded-secret detection before reading files:
#     grep -rn "password\s*=\s*['\"][^'\"]" .
#     grep -rn "api_key\s*=\s*['\"][^'\"]" .
#     grep -rn "secret\s*=\s*['\"][^'\"]" .

## 5.2  PII protection
# - Never include real personal data (names, emails, addresses, IDs)
#   in logs, error messages, or tool output.
# - Anonymize or mask before processing.

## 5.3  Path traversal prevention
# - Validate ALL file paths against an allowedRoots whitelist.
# - Reject paths containing ".." or absolute paths outside allowed roots.
# - Enforce this check before any filesystem operation.

## 5.4  Input validation
# - Validate every tool input against its JSON Schema using Zod (or
#   equivalent) at the handler boundary.
# - Reject unexpected fields (strict mode).
# - Sanitize strings before use in shell commands or SQL queries.

## 5.5  Documentation
# - Record every significant security decision in docs/adr/.


# ================================================================
# § 6  PROMPT TEMPLATES (src/prompts/)
# ================================================================
#
# - All templates are English Markdown files.
# - Each template must include a version header:
#     <!-- prompt-version: 1.0.0 | tool: <name> | updated: YYYY-MM-DD -->
# - Templates must instruct the LLM to:
#     • Never reproduce credential values.
#     • Tag unknowns with [UNKNOWN] instead of guessing.
#     • Flag security issues with 🔴.
#     • Request confirmation before irreversible actions.
# - Keep prompts deterministic: prefer explicit output schemas over
#   open-ended instructions.


# ================================================================
# § 7  TESTING STRATEGY
# ================================================================
#
# - Unit tests      : pure functions, parsers, validators, redaction logic.
# - Integration     : each tool handler with realistic fixture data.
# - Fixtures        : minimal real-world samples per use case.
#                     Non-English content in fixtures is allowed.
# - Coverage        : >= 80% line coverage enforced on CI.
# - Test file names : *.test.ts co-located with source;
#                     integration tests under tests/integration/.
# - Test labels     : English only (describe / it strings).
# - CI must pass    : lint + type-check + unit + integration.


# ================================================================
# § 8  GIT & COLLABORATION + AI ASSISTANT BEHAVIOR
# ================================================================

## 8.1  Commit messages — Conventional Commits (English only)
#
#   <type>(<scope>): <short summary in imperative mood>
#
#   Types : feat | fix | docs | test | refactor | chore | security
#
#   Examples:
#     feat(tools): add file-inventory tool
#     fix(security): prevent path traversal in file reader
#     docs(adr): record decision on secret redaction strategy

## 8.2  Branch names (kebab-case, type-prefixed)
#   feat/file-inventory-tool
#   fix/path-traversal-validation
#   docs/update-readme

## 8.3  Pull Requests
#   • Title: same format as commit messages (English).
#   • Description: English; link related issues; include test evidence.
#   • Do NOT merge without passing CI.
#   • At least one reviewer approval required.

## 8.4  AI assistant rules
#
# When an AI assistant (Cursor, Claude, Copilot, etc.) generates or
# edits code in this repository:
#
# ALWAYS ✅
#   • Write all code, comments, identifiers, and strings in English.
#   • Add JSDoc to every exported function and class.
#   • Validate tool inputs against the declared JSON Schema.
#   • Apply secret redaction before any file content leaves the server.
#   • Validate file paths against allowedRoots before fs operations.
#   • Return structured MCP errors ({ isError: true, ... }) on failure.
#   • Write a corresponding test for every new tool or utility.
#   • Use [UNKNOWN] for values that cannot be determined.
#   • Add a confirmation gate for any irreversible operation.
#
# NEVER ❌
#   • Write comments, identifiers, or string literals in Japanese.
#     (§ 9 developer notes are the ONLY exception.)
#   • Use the `any` type in TypeScript.
#   • Log or return raw credential or PII values.
#   • Suppress or swallow errors without logging.
#   • Fabricate or guess unknown values — use [UNKNOWN].
#   • Perform filesystem operations without path validation.
#   • Merge code that fails lint, type-check, or tests.


